@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Program History"
1.  Introduction


Ever been using @{"Mathscript 3" link "MathScript" 0} and wanted to quickly insert a new code into
the formula, without having to navigate through the 14 separate banks of
code icons?  Sounds like you need a button bar...and lookee here, that's
just what QuickCode gives you!

Yes, thanks to the combination of @{"Gui4CLI" link "g4c" 0} and ARexx, QuickCode gives you
a button bar holding up to 10 codes, all ready for inserting with just a
single mouse click.


NOTE!!!

QuickCode is designed for use with Mathscript 3.1+.  If you are still using
Mathscript 3.0, you should really upgrade right NOW!  Considering it's not
going to cost you anything (your 3.0 keyfile will unlock all the other 3.x
versions as well), there's no reason not to upgrade.  


HappyEnv users take note:

I've had one report of HappyEnv causing the Quickcode Env: variable to
become corrupted.  I can't do anything about this, since I don't control
how Gui4CLI interacts with HappyEnv when reading/writing env variables.


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Introduction"
2.  Installation


Note: If you've already got Gui4CLI *V3* installed, start at step 3.

1: Copy Gui and Gui4CLI into your c: directory.

2: ASSIGN Guis: c:


3: Copy the QC directory anywhere you like.

4: Put QuickCode and QuickCode.guide wherever you like.

5: Edit the QuickCode file so that instead of reading:

   echo "Where is your QuickCode.gc file?"
 
	it actually contains c:gui, followed by the path to QuickCode.gc
	
	
	For example, my QuickCode file looks like this:
	
	c:gui mathscript:rexx/qc/quickcode.gc
	
      
And that's it!


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Author Info"
@prev "Installation"
3. Usage


If you can use Mathscript, you can use QuickCode...

When QuickCode starts, it opens the button bar, which consists of a
small non-sizable window holding 10 definable buttons and a CLEAR button.  
If this is the first time you've run QuickCode, all the definable buttons 
will be blank, and do nothing when pressed.

To define your own buttons, select the Settings..Change menu option (or
use the RAmiga-C shortcut), which opens the @{"prefs window." link "Prefs" 0}

Once you've defined your buttons, simply click on the one you want to
insert, and it'll be inserted at the current cursor location in your
formula, just as if you'd selected the code directly from Mathscript.

Clicking on the CLEAR button will wipe EVERYTHING in the Mathscript
formula window, so use it with caution!  


@{b}NEW for 1.8!@{ub}  Selecting the Snapshot option from the Settings menu
will save the current bar location, so that the next time QuickCode is run,
the bar opens in the same place.  No more dragging it down from the top-left
corner of the screen every time :-)

Notes:

QuickCode will default to running on the Workbench screen.  You can make it 
run on a different public screen (the Final Writer screen for instance), by 
using the Ctrl-J hotkey to jump the GUI onto whichever screen you want to use.
The next time you come to run QuickCode, it will remember which screen was last
used and open on it if available, or on the Workbench if it isn't.

The Gui4CLI interpreter installs an entry in the Workbench Tools menu.
Unless you're familiar with Gui4CLI, leave well alone!  There are no
situations where you'll ever need to use the options provided by this
menu choice, and if you do start experimenting with them, the most likely
result is that you'll cause QuickCode to stop working.

You must have ARexx installed and running before using QuickCode.

     
@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0} 
@endnode

@node "Prefs" "Prefs Window"
The Prefs Window...


Along the top of this window are copies of your current buttons, and
directly below each button is a small blue indicator.  Whichever
button is currently selected for change will have its indicator filled
in, and the other indicators will be unfilled.

To alter a button, select it if necessary by clicking on it, then select
the desired formula code from the large gadget at the bottom left of
the window.  To alter the currently displayed selection, click on one of
the 14 bank select icons to the right of the selection gadget.  You'll
see that these icons are identical to the icons you use in Mathscript, so
you shouldn't have any trouble navigating (I hope!)

Once the desired formula code icon is displayed in the selection gadget,
simply click on it and the selected button will be updated with this
formula code.  If you want to clear a button, simply click on any of the
blank icons in the selection area.


Finally, at the bottom of the window are a few on/off options.

@{b}Quit Gui4CLI on close@{ub}

If you select this option, then the Gui4CLI interpreter will be removed
from the system when you exit QuickCode.  

This option is now safeguarded, so that even with it turned on, Gui4CLI
will only be removed if QuickCode is the only Gui loaded.  If QuickCode
detects any other Guis in the system, it will NOT close Gui4CLI.


@{b}Show Clear Button@{ub}

Turns the CLEAR button on or off.


@{b}Query on Clear@{ub}

If the CLEAR button is on, this turns the "Are you Sure?" requester
on and off.
 

Once you've updated your buttons, click the close gadget to return to the
normal button bar, where you'll see your new choices ready for use.  Note
that closing the prefs window also saves your new prefs, you don't have
to do it yourself.


NOTE:

If upon returning from the Prefs window, you end up with a blank button bar,
then try re-doing your prefs.  If you still get a blank bar, then LET ME
KNOW!!!  This *was* an actual bug in the code, but as of V1.5 it should have
been removed.


@{"Return to Usage" link "Usage" 0}
@endnode

