@node "g4c" "Gui4CLI"
What's this Gui4CLI he keeps mentioning...


Gui4CLI is a really neat utility for generating GUIs from simple ASCII
scripts.  Though it isn't perfect (but what is), it's about the easiest
way to create GUIs ranging from the incredibly simple to the absurdly
complex.  If I'd had to teach myself how to use any of the alternative
GUI utils that are available for ARexx, I'd still be pratting on with
alpha versions of QuickCode.

And believe me, Gui4CLI is capable of FAR more than QuickCode shows.


You can find the complete and most up-to-date Gui4CLI package on Aminet, 
as Dev/Gui/Gui4Cli.lha, or at the Gui4CLI homepage.


The Gui and Gui4CLI executables supplied in this archive are copyright to 
Dimitris C. Keletsekis.  Any questions you may have about Gui4CLI
should be directed to him at:

                       dck@prometheus.hol.gr
                       
or you can check the Gui4CLI homepage at:

                http://users.hol.gr/~dck/gcmain.htm
              
                       
I suggest that if you do have any questions, you first get the full Gui4CLI
package and read through the documentation.  You might even decide to try
writing some GUIs of your own - it really is quite good fun!


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Things" "Things still to do..."  
The palette used by the GUI is based on the Workbench 3.0 default.  If you
have an alternative palette, the icons may not look correct.  There isn't
that much I can do about this, since this is a generic problem with
interfaces that don't own the screen they're running on.

However, there is also the problem of the swapped black and white palette
entries between WB2+ and WB1.x, which becomes apparent if, for instance,
you run QuickCode on the Final Writer pubscreen.  I should be able to
put in a fix for this, although it may mean having two copies of each
icon...  This *may* be included in a future version.


QuickCode assumes that the Mathscript Rexx port is named MATHSCRIPT.1  Now,
the only reason it won't be called this is if you're running multiple
copies of Mathscript, in which case I have to ask WHY???.  If someone emails
me with a very good reason why they need to run more than one copy (and 
therefore need the ability to alter the Mathscript Rexx port), then I'll
consider adding this ability.


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode
